# Testing Conventions

## Setup

- Use **Vitest** for all unit and integration tests.
- Co-locate test files: `<module>.test.ts` sits next to `<module>.ts`.
- Never import the real Prisma client in tests — always mock it.

## Structure

- One behavior per `it()` block — do not test multiple things in one assertion block.
- Group related tests with `describe()`.
- Use `vi.mock()` at the top of the file, before `describe()`.

```ts
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from "vitest";
import { createInvite } from "@/actions/team-members";

vi.mock("@/lib/prisma", () => ({
  prisma: {
    invite: {
      create: vi.fn(),
    },
  },
}));

import { prisma } from "@/lib/prisma";

describe("createInvite", () => {
  beforeEach(() => vi.clearAllMocks());

  it("returns created invite on valid input", async () => {
    vi.mocked(prisma.invite.create).mockResolvedValue({ id: "1", email: "worker@example.com" });
    const form = new FormData();
    form.append("email", "worker@example.com");
    const result = await createInvite(form);
    expect(result.data?.email).toBe("worker@example.com");
  });

  it("returns validation error when email is missing", async () => {
    const result = await createInvite(new FormData());
    expect(result.error).toBeDefined();
    expect(prisma.invite.create).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
});
```

## What to Test

- ✅ Business logic functions and server actions
- ✅ Permission helpers (`requireRole`, org access checks, invite rules)
- ✅ Time and pay calculations
- ✅ Zod schema validation edge cases
- ✅ Custom hooks (use `renderHook` from `@testing-library/react`)
- ❌ Don't test framework internals (Next.js routing, Prisma internals)
- ❌ Don't test implementation details — test observable behavior

## Naming

- `it("returns X when Y")` — describe input → expected output.
- Avoid vague names like `it("works")` or `it("handles error")`.
